Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888800022&r=1&w=2">Re: leading digits in domain names</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837783700011&r=1&w=2">"J. Spencer Love" &lt;JSLove () MIT-MULTICS ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198704">1987-04-22 23:59:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926848&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926848&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

The Multics implementation is perfectly happy with names which begin
with digits.  The criteria for addresses require that the only
characters be decimal digits and dots.  Thus, even a single alphabetic
character causes the string to be unambiguously rejected as an internet
address.  As long as there are no top-level domains which are all
numeric, there is no possibility for abuse with fully qualified names.

For domains other than in-addr.arpa, I think that components of domain
names which are entirely numeric are a bad idea (components are what
come between periods).  However, I see no problem with components like
"3Com".  If this requires changing the specification, I have no
objection.  I don't even think that names which are all numeric should
be forbidden; just that users who try to use such names in partially
qualified form deserve what they get.
                                        -- Spencer

